```

---

## 5. Request lifecycle

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant UI as Streamlit UI
    participant API as FastAPI /query
    participant Safety as Safety Checker
    participant Rx as RxNorm Normalizer
    participant R as Hybrid Retriever
    participant G as Graph Retriever
    participant LLM as External LLM
    participant V as Validators
    participant A as Audit Logger

    User->>UI: Ask biomedical evidence question
    UI->>API: POST /query
    API->>Safety: Classify and safety pre-check

    alt Personal medical advice
        Safety-->>API: Block request
        API-->>UI: Safe refusal + redirect
        UI-->>User: Refusal response
    else Safe evidence question
        Safety->>Rx: Normalize drug entities
        Rx-->>API: Normalized drug IDs and names
        API->>R: Retrieve label/literature/vector evidence
        R->>G: Retrieve graph relationships
        G-->>R: Graph paths
        R-->>API: Evidence bundle
        API->>LLM: Generate structured answer from evidence only
        LLM-->>API: Draft answer + claims
        API->>V: Validate citations, claims, graph consistency, safety
        V-->>API: Validation results
        API->>A: Store audit record
        A-->>API: audit_id
        API-->>UI: Structured response
        UI-->>User: Answer + evidence trace
    end
```

---

## 6. Component responsibilities

### 6.1 Streamlit Evidence Trace UI

The UI is responsible for making the internal governance path visible.

It should display:

* original user question
* safety classification
* normalized drug entities
* retrieved DailyMed sections
* retrieved PubMed abstracts
* graph paths
* generated claims
* claim-source mapping
* validation status
* safety result
* audit ID

The UI should make it obvious that the answer is an evidence summary, not medical advice.

---

### 6.2 FastAPI backend

The backend coordinates the full request lifecycle.

Initial endpoints:

```text
GET /health
POST /query
```

Planned endpoints:

```text
GET /drugs
GET /audit/{audit_id}
GET /graph/{drug_name}
```

The backend should remain thin.

Business logic should live in named modules:

```text
classification
normalization
retrieval
graph
generation
validation
safety
audit
```

---

### 6.3 Query classifier

The classifier determines what kind of query the user asked.

Initial query classes:

```text
label_summary
warning_question
contraindication_question
adverse_reaction_question
drug_interaction_evidence_question
pubmed_literature_question
multi_hop_evidence_question
personal_medical_advice
out_of_scope
```

The most important early behavior is blocking personal medical advice before retrieval and generation.

---

### 6.4 Safety checker

The safety checker runs twice:

```text
1. before retrieval and generation
2. after generation before response
```

The first check blocks obviously unsafe questions.

The final check catches unsafe language that may appear in the generated answer.

Blocked examples:

```text
Should I take this medication?
Should I stop taking this medication?
What dose should I take?
Can I combine these two medications?
Is this drug safe for me?
Is my symptom caused by this drug?
```

Safe redirect example:

```text
I cannot provide personal medical advice or determine whether a medication is appropriate for you. I can summarize what public drug labels and biomedical literature say, but you should consult a qualified healthcare professional for personal decisions.
```

---

### 6.5 Drug/entity extractor

The entity extractor identifies biomedical entities in the query.

MVP entities:

```text
drug names
brand names
generic names
risk terms
label section terms
population terms
```

Initial controlled drug set:

```text
metformin
warfarin
atorvastatin
semaglutide
ibuprofen
acetaminophen
amoxicillin
lisinopril
```

---

### 6.6 RxNorm normalizer

The normalizer maps user-provided names to normalized drug concepts.

Examples:

```text
Tylenol       → acetaminophen
Advil         → ibuprofen
Glucophage    → metformin
Coumadin      → warfarin
```

The normalized entity should include:

```text
original_text
normalized_name
rxnorm_id
entity_type
confidence
```

---

### 6.7 Hybrid evidence retriever

The hybrid retriever collects evidence from several sources.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Query["Normalized Query"] --> Hybrid["Hybrid Evidence Retriever"]

    Hybrid --> Label["DailyMed Label Retrieval"]
    Hybrid --> Lit["PubMed Literature Retrieval"]
    Hybrid --> Vector["Vector Similarity Search"]
    Hybrid --> Graph["Graph Relationship Lookup"]

    Label --> Bundle["Evidence Bundle"]
    Lit --> Bundle
    Vector --> Bundle
    Graph --> Bundle
```

The retriever should return an evidence bundle, not free text.

---

### 6.8 DailyMed retriever

The DailyMed retriever fetches public label sections.

Important sections:

```text
warnings and precautions
contraindications
adverse reactions
drug interactions
use in specific populations
boxed warning
```

The system may retrieve dosage sections for completeness, but it must not provide personal dosing guidance.

---

### 6.9 PubMed retriever

The PubMed retriever fetches public literature metadata and abstracts.

It should return:

```text
PMID
title
abstract
journal
publication year
query used
source URL or source identifier
```

PubMed evidence should be summarized cautiously.

The system should not overstate literature findings.

---

### 6.10 Vector retriever

The vector retriever finds semantically relevant chunks from cached label and literature text.

MVP store:

```text
Chroma
```

Later option:

```text
Postgres + pgvector
```

The vector retriever helps find relevant passages, but it is not enough by itself.

That is why the graph and validators exist.

---

### 6.11 Neo4j graph retriever

The graph retriever validates relationships between biomedical entities.

Example graph path:

```text
Drug(warfarin)
  -[:HAS_WARNING]->
Warning(bleeding risk)
  -[:SUPPORTED_BY]->
LabelSection(warnings and precautions)
```

The graph should help answer:

```text
Which warning is connected to this drug?
Which label section supports this warning?
Which PubMed article discusses this concept?
Which two drugs are connected through an interaction or shared risk?
```

---

### 6.12 External LLM generator

The LLM generator receives an evidence bundle and must return structured output.

The LLM should not decide whether a claim is valid.

It only drafts an answer and claim list.

Validation happens after generation.

Required behavior:

```text
use retrieved evidence only
do not provide personal medical advice
return structured claims
include source references
express uncertainty when evidence is insufficient
```

---

### 6.13 Evidence contract builder

The evidence contract turns generated output into auditable structured records.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Draft["Generated Draft Answer"] --> Claims["Extract Claims"]
    Claims --> Sources["Map Claims to Source IDs"]
    Sources --> GraphPaths["Attach Graph Path IDs"]
    GraphPaths --> Contract["Evidence Contract"]
    Contract --> Validators["Validation Pipeline"]
```

Each claim should include:

```text
claim_text
claim_type
drug_entities
relationship_type
supporting_source_ids
graph_path_ids
allowed_strength
validation_status
```

---

### 6.14 Validators

The validation subsystem checks whether the answer is safe and supported.

Validators:

```text
citation validator
claim validator
graph consistency validator
safety validator
```

Validation states:

```text
supported
partially_supported
unsupported
conflicting
not_checked
```

If a claim is unsupported, the system should either remove it, mark it clearly, or return an insufficient-evidence response.

---

### 6.15 Audit logger

The audit logger stores the full response trace.

Audit record should include:

```text
audit_id
timestamp
user_query
query_classification
normalized_entities
retrieved_sources
graph_paths
generated_claims
validation_results
safety_result
final_answer
```

The audit log is what turns this from a demo chatbot into an inspectable governed system.

---

## 7. Data flow

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Q["User Query"] --> QR["QueryRequest"]

    QR --> QC["QueryClassification"]
    QC --> SR1["SafetyPolicyResult"]

    SR1 -->|allowed| NE["NormalizedEntity[]"]
    SR1 -->|blocked| BR["BlockedResponse"]

    NE --> LS["DrugLabelSection[]"]
    NE --> PE["PubMedEvidence[]"]
    NE --> GP["GraphPath[]"]
    NE --> VC["VectorChunk[]"]

    LS --> EB["EvidenceBundle"]
    PE --> EB
    GP --> EB
    VC --> EB

    EB --> GA["GeneratedAnswer"]
    GA --> EC["EvidenceClaim[]"]

    EC --> VR["ValidationResult"]
    GP --> VR
    EB --> VR

    VR --> SR2["Final SafetyPolicyResult"]

    SR2 --> AR["AuditRecord"]
    AR --> RESP["QueryResponse"]
```

---

## 8. Graph schema

```mermaid
erDiagram
    Drug ||--o{ Ingredient : HAS_INGREDIENT
    Drug ||--o{ BrandName : HAS_BRAND_NAME
    Drug ||--o{ LabelSection : HAS_LABEL_SECTION
    Drug ||--o{ Warning : HAS_WARNING
    Drug ||--o{ Contraindication : HAS_CONTRAINDICATION
    Drug ||--o{ AdverseReaction : HAS_ADVERSE_REACTION
    Drug ||--o{ DrugInteraction : HAS_INTERACTION
    Drug ||--o{ Population : HAS_POPULATION_WARNING
    PubMedArticle ||--o{ Warning : DISCUSSES
    EvidenceClaim ||--o{ LabelSection : SUPPORTED_BY
    EvidenceClaim ||--o{ PubMedArticle : SUPPORTED_BY
    EvidenceClaim ||--o{ Drug : HAS_GRAPH_PATH
```

Node types:

```text
Drug
Ingredient
BrandName
LabelSection
Warning
Contraindication
AdverseReaction
DrugInteraction
Population
PubMedArticle
EvidenceClaim
```

Relationship types:

```text
HAS_INGREDIENT
HAS_BRAND_NAME
HAS_LABEL_SECTION
HAS_WARNING
HAS_CONTRAINDICATION
HAS_ADVERSE_REACTION
HAS_INTERACTION
HAS_POPULATION_WARNING
DISCUSSES
SUPPORTED_BY
HAS_GRAPH_PATH
```

---

## 9. Evidence contract structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class GeneratedAnswer {
        string answer_text
        EvidenceClaim[] claims
        Citation[] citations
        ValidationResult validation_result
        SafetyPolicyResult safety_result
        string audit_id
    }

    class EvidenceClaim {
        string claim_text
        string claim_type
        string[] drug_entities
        string relationship_type
        string[] supporting_source_ids
        string[] graph_path_ids
        string allowed_strength
        string validation_status
    }

    class Citation {
        string source_id
        string source_type
        string title
        string section
        string url
    }

    class ValidationResult {
        string status
        string[] supported_claim_ids
        string[] unsupported_claim_ids
        string[] warnings
    }

    class SafetyPolicyResult {
        bool allowed
        string reason
        string response_mode
    }

    GeneratedAnswer --> EvidenceClaim
    GeneratedAnswer --> Citation
    GeneratedAnswer --> ValidationResult
    GeneratedAnswer --> SafetyPolicyResult
```

---

## 10. Runtime paths

### Safe evidence query

```text
User asks:
"What does the official label say about warnings for warfarin?"

System path:
1. Classify as warning_question.
2. Safety pre-check allows the query.
3. Extract warfarin.
4. Normalize through RxNorm.
5. Retrieve DailyMed warning sections.
6. Retrieve optional PubMed evidence.
7. Retrieve graph warning relationships.
8. Build evidence bundle.
9. Generate structured answer.
10. Validate claims and citations.
11. Validate graph paths.
12. Run final safety check.
13. Store audit record.
14. Return answer with evidence trace.
```

---

### Blocked personal advice query

```text
User asks:
"Should I take warfarin with ibuprofen?"

System path:
1. Classify as personal_medical_advice.
2. Safety pre-check blocks the advice request.
3. Return refusal.
4. Offer safe redirect to public label/literature summary.
5. Store audit record.
```

Expected behavior:

```text
I cannot provide personal medical advice or determine whether medications are appropriate for you. I can summarize what public drug labels and biomedical literature say about warfarin, NSAID-class medications, and bleeding-related warnings.
```

---

### Multi-hop GraphRAG query

```text
User asks:
"What label warnings and PubMed evidence discuss bleeding risk with warfarin and ibuprofen?"

System path:
1. Classify as multi_hop_evidence_question.
2. Safety pre-check allows evidence summary but blocks personal advice.
3. Extract warfarin, ibuprofen, and bleeding risk.
4. Normalize drugs through RxNorm.
5. Retrieve DailyMed label sections for both drugs.
6. Retrieve PubMed abstracts about relevant concepts.
7. Query graph for drug-warning-risk relationships.
8. Build evidence bundle.
9. Generate answer using evidence only.
10. Validate claim-source support.
11. Validate graph relationship support.
12. Run final safety check.
13. Store audit trace.
14. Return answer and evidence map.
```

---

## 11. Failure-mode design

| Failure mode               | Example                                    | Mitigation                              |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------- |
| Unsafe advice              | “Should I take this?”                      | safety pre-check and final safety check |
| Unsupported claim          | LLM invents relationship                   | claim-source validation                 |
| Citation laundering        | cited source does not support claim        | citation validator                      |
| Graph mismatch             | answer claims unsupported relationship     | graph consistency validator             |
| Insufficient evidence      | system answers confidently without support | evidence sufficiency check              |
| Entity normalization error | brand mapped to wrong generic              | RxNorm normalization and confidence     |
| Retrieval failure          | PubMed or DailyMed unavailable             | retries, caching, audit error states    |
| Overstated literature      | abstract treated as clinical guidance      | conservative answer policy              |
| Missing audit trace        | response cannot be inspected later         | audit required before final response    |

---

## 12. MVP deployment shape

For the MVP, all services run locally.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Browser["Browser"] --> Streamlit["Streamlit<br/>localhost:8501"]
    Streamlit --> FastAPI["FastAPI<br/>localhost:8000"]

    FastAPI --> Env[".env Settings"]
    FastAPI --> Cache["Cached Source Files"]
    FastAPI --> Chroma["Chroma Vector Store"]
    FastAPI --> Neo4j["Neo4j<br/>localhost:7474 / 7687"]
    FastAPI --> AuditDB["DuckDB / SQLite Audit DB"]
    FastAPI --> LLM["External LLM API"]

    FastAPI --> DailyMed["DailyMed API"]
    FastAPI --> RxNav["RxNav API"]
    FastAPI --> PubMed["NCBI E-utilities"]
```

MVP local services:

```text
FastAPI backend
Streamlit frontend
Neo4j graph database
local vector store
local audit database
cached source files
external LLM API
public biomedical APIs
```

